# SwyftDesktop — Research & Development Notes

This document records the technical decisions, discoveries, failures, and architectural direction of the SwyftDesktop project.

It is intended to be understandable even to readers without programming experience.

---

# 1. Project Goal (What is being built)

SwyftDesktop is a system that connects a mobile device and a desktop environment into a single interactive system.

It aims to:

- Turn a phone into a control hub
- Run a custom desktop environment on a PC
- Allow both devices to work together in real time
- Keep the phone usable while controlling the desktop

---

# 2. Core Idea (Simple Explanation)

Instead of:

- Phone doing phone things
- PC doing PC things

The system makes:

- Phone = controller + input device + app launcher
- PC = display + execution environment

Both are connected through a communication bridge.

---

# 3. System Structure

The system is split into 3 layers:

## 📱 Mobile Layer
Handles:
- App launching
- User interface
- Input (future: keyboard + trackpad)
- Sending commands

## 🌐 Bridge Layer
Handles:
- Communication between devices
- Sending actions (like "open app")
- Sending input (mouse, keyboard)

## 💻 Desktop Layer
Handles:
- Custom desktop UI
- Running applications
- Displaying windows and widgets

---

# 4. What Has Been Built So Far (Mobile)

## Working Features
- Basic Android app created
- Simple UI using buttons and layouts
- Ability to launch apps using package names
- App discovery using Android PackageManager (partial)

## Problems Encountered
- App list initially only showed a few system apps
- UI was built using basic vertical layouts (not scalable)
- Some Android functions require newer API levels than expected
- Confusion around proper project structure in Android Studio

---

# 5. Key Fixes Learned

## App Launching
Apps are launched using:

- Package name (example: `com.brave.browser`)
- Android Intent system

If the system cannot find the launch activity:
- The app cannot be opened directly
- A fallback error is required

---

## App Listing Issue
Only showing a few apps happens because:

- Some apps are not marked as "launcher apps"
- Android filters apps using `CATEGORY_LAUNCHER`
- System apps and restricted apps may be hidden

---

## UI Structure Issue
Initial UI problems occurred because:

- Multiple layouts were declared incorrectly
- Views were added outside proper lifecycle scope
- Android requires UI setup inside `onCreate()`

---

## Kotlin Compilation Errors
Common causes:
- Functions declared outside class scope
- Incorrect braces placement
- Missing or duplicated variables
- Mixing UI logic and declarations incorrectly

---

# 6. Current Architecture Decision

The project is moving away from:

❌ Direct UI logic (buttons doing everything)

Towards:

✔ Action-based system

Meaning:

- UI triggers actions
- Actions are handled centrally
- Logic is separated from interface

Example:

User presses button → Action created → System executes action

